    "context": "Continual learning for AI agents refers to the ability of an agent system to improve its performance over time based on new data, feedback, and experience. Unlike traditional software that remains static after deployment, AI agents can adapt their behavior through multiple mechanisms. This is critical because production environments constantly surface new edge cases, user patterns, and domain shifts that the original training data did not cover.\nContinual learning at the model layer involves updating the model weights through techniques like fine-tuning, reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), or direct preference optimization (DPO). This is the most common interpretation of continual learning but also the most expensive and disruptive, as it requires retraining or adapting the underlying foundation model. Model-layer updates are best suited for systematic improvements across many interactions rather than fixing individual failures.\nContinual learning at the harness layer means modifying the orchestration logic, tool selection, or routing rules that control how the agent operates. For example, updating a LangGraph state machine to add a new tool node or adjusting retry logic based on observed failure patterns. Continual learning at the context layer involves updating the instructions, few-shot examples, or retrieval knowledge that the agent draws on at inference time, without changing either the model or the harness code.",
